{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619013","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619013"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:27:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:27:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16524"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16524","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16524"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9215"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75402"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9215"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16524"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60912"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6087"},{"type":"tags","id":"10274"},{"type":"tags","id":"10333"},{"type":"tags","id":"10334"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21850"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21852"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75402"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset bilateral leg weakness. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His vital signs are stable. Neurological examination reveals increased tone and weakness in both legs with hyperreflexia and bilateral upgoing plantar responses. Sensation to pinprick is reduced below the T8 dermatome. Upper limb examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pattern of muscle tone in this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Descending upper motor neuron pattern","Ascending lower motor neuron pattern","Descending lower motor neuron pattern","Ascending upper motor neuron pattern","Mixed upper and lower motor neuron pattern"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features consistent with an upper motor neuron lesion affecting the spinal cord at approximately the T8 level. The key findings supporting this are increased tone, weakness, hyperreflexia, and upgoing plantar responses below the level of the lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDescending upper motor neuron pattern\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes the findings in this case. In upper motor neuron lesions, there is increased muscle tone and hyperreflexia in muscles innervated by segments below the level of the lesion, while segments above remain normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAscending lower motor neuron pattern\u003C/strong\u003E would show decreased tone and areflexia starting from the lowest segments and progressing upwards, as might be seen in Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDescending lower motor neuron pattern\u003C/strong\u003E would show decreased tone and areflexia below the level of the lesion, which is not consistent with the findings here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAscending upper motor neuron pattern\u003C/strong\u003E is not physiologically possible as upper motor neurons descend from the cortex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMixed upper and lower motor neuron pattern\u003C/strong\u003E would show features of both UMN and LMN lesions at the same level, as might be seen in conditions like motor neurone disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUpper motor neuron lesions typically result from conditions affecting the cortex, internal capsule, brainstem, or spinal cord. Common causes include stroke, trauma, tumours, or inflammatory conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Upper motor neuron lesions cause increased tone, hyperreflexia and upgoing plantar responses below the level of the lesion.","The pattern of neurological findings helps distinguish between upper and lower motor neuron lesions.","Spasticity develops gradually over days to weeks following an acute upper motor neuron lesion."],"references":["Javed K, Reddy V, Lui F. Neuroanatomy, Lateral Corticospinal Tract. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534818/","Lemon RN. Descending pathways in motor control. Annu Rev Neurosci. 2008;31:195-218. doi: 10.1146/annurev.neuro.31.060407.125547. PMID: 18558853.","Menon P, Vucic S. The Upper Motor Neuron-Improved Knowledge from ALS and Related Clinical Disorders. Brain Sci. 2021 Jul 21;11(8):958. doi: 10.3390/brainsci11080958. PMID: 34439577; PMCID: PMC8392624.","Shirota Y, Otsuka J, Toda T, Hamada M. Neurophysiological differentiation of upper motor neuron damage in neurodegenerative disorders. Clin Neurophysiol Pract. 2022 Sep 23;7:273-278. doi: 10.1016/j.cnp.2022.09.002. PMID: 36263296; PMCID: PMC9574772."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60912"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16524"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60912"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T19:29:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-29T19:31:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9215"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisi